{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17488775","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17488775"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T03:56:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T03:56:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"535"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"535","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/535"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.07,0.28,0.09,0.49]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"535"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112163"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"535","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/535"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"535"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94228"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"106"},{"type":"tags","id":"111"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9099"},{"type":"tags","id":"9230"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2492"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2563"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26875"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39920"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42095"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112163","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/112163"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 72-year-old woman presents with sudden onset severe and generalised abdominal pain of six hours duration, associated with nausea and vomiting. Her medical history is significant for hypertension and hyperlipidaemia. Her regular medications include perindopril 4 mg mane and atorvastatin 20 mg nocte.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her blood pressure is 90/60 mmHg, pulse 100/min and irregularly irregular, respiratory rate 24/min with SpO\u003Csub\u003E2\u003C/sub\u003E 98% on room air. Her temperature is 37.4C. The abdomen is markedly distended and there is diffuse abdominal tenderness with rebound. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIntravenous resuscitation fluids are started. An urgent CT abdomen/pelvis scan shows dilated loops of small bowel with submucosal gas bubbles.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Broad spectrum antibiotics and observe","Pain relief and observe","CT angiogram","Intravenous heparin","Laparoscopy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is acutely unwell with an intra-abdominal problem. Even without the radiological findings, the clinician will be considering an ischaemic event. In this case, the CT findings of intramural bowel gas (pneumatosis intestinalis) is virtually diagnostic of mesenteric ischaemia. Whilst there can be other, more benign, explanations for the radiological finding of gas within the wall of the bowel, such as pulmonary disease and agents causing abnormal mucosal permeability, these are very unlikely explanations here, given the clinical picture.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has mesenteric ischaemia, which has almost certainly been caused by an embolus from her atrial fibrillation (new diagnosis at this presentation and is therefore not anticoagulated) becoming lodged in the superior mesenteric artery or one of its branches. It may be too late to do anything to retrieve the situation, but urgent surgical intervention should be considered - particularly if the patient was in good health before this event. This patient is shocked and a more conservative approach, such as CT angiography with subsequent attempts at embolectomy, would produce a potentially fatal delay in her management. An early \u003Cstrong\u003Elaparoscopic assessment\u003C/strong\u003E enables the surgeons to quickly and directly assess bowel viability, enabling prompt restoration of mesenteric blood flow. Indications for CT angiography with embolectomy include: no signs of shock (i.e. normotensive, nil tachycardia) and no signs of bowel infarction (i.e. no peritonism and/or distension).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is important to appreciate that this is a potentially fatal event and the family should be counselled appropriately. If there is extensive infarction and surgical resection is considered futile that it is easier to provide palliation after a laparoscopy rather than a formal laparotomy. However, if the patient had obvious peritonitis and surgical resection was going to be considered, then a laparotomy as the initial approach could be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf this patient was haemodynamically stable and without evidence of peritonitis, then a \u003Cstrong\u003ECT angiogram\u003C/strong\u003E could be done to define the site and the extent of the arterial occlusion. Once this has been done and the obstruction overcome, \u003Cstrong\u003Eheparin\u003C/strong\u003E could be given.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this particular case, the patient was previously is good health and efforts should be made towards resuscitation and intervention, rather than palliation with \u003Cstrong\u003Epain relief and observation\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered in the acute immediate management of this problem, but they would not be the sole planned intervention. If management was aimed primarily at palliation, there would not be a place for antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Laparoscopic assessment is key in the early management of mesenteric ischaemia.","Consider mesenteric ischaemic for CT findings of pneumatosis intestinalis and signs of shock."],"references":["Dang, CV 2019, Acute Mesenteric Ischemia: Background, Anatomy, Pathophysiology, Medscape, viewed 26 April 2021, \u003Chttps://emedicine.medscape.com/article/189146-overview\u003E.","Bala M, Kashuk J, Moore EE. Acute mesenteric ischemia: guidelines of the World Society of Emergency Surgery. World J Emerg Surg. 2017;12:38. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28794797/","Schofield, N, Webb, ST, Varcada, M \u0026 Macfie, A 2014, \u2018Acute Mesenteric Ischaemia\u2019, Journal of the Intensive Care Society. 2014;15(3). Available at: https://journals.sagepub.com/doi/pdf/10.1177/175114371401500310"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94228"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"535"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"94228","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/94228"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-26T09:23:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-26T09:23:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"535"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"112163"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount